  "prompt": "Does it possible to pursue LLB after BE mechanical?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to pursue an LLB (Bachelor of Laws) after completing a BE (Bachelor of Engineering) in Mechanical Engineering. Here are some key points to consider:\n\n1. Eligibility:\n- Most law schools require a bachelor's degree from a recognized university\n- Minimum aggregate marks (usually 45-50%) in the qualifying degree\n- No specific restriction on the stream of previous graduation\n\n2. Admission process:\n- CLAT (Common Law Admission Test)\n- LSAT India\n- University-specific entrance exams\n- Some universities might conduct their own entrance tests\n\n3. Duration:\n- Regular LLB: 3 years\n- Integrated LLB: 5 years\n\n4. Advantages of pursuing law after engineering:\n- Diverse career opportunities\n- Technical knowledge can be beneficial in intellectual property law\n- Option to specialize in patent law or technology-related legal areas\n- Potential for interdisciplinary career paths\n\n5. Career options:\n- Intellectual property lawyer\n- Technology law consultant\n- Patent attorney\n- Corporate legal advisor\n- Legal consultant in technical domains\n\nKeep in mind that specific requirements may vary between institutions, so it's recommended to check individual university guidelines.",
